Getting married in the Catholic Church in Saint Vincent and the Grenadines

Very few inter-church marriages take place in the country, as Catholics are urged to get married in the church where either of the spouses resides.

The Church usually discourages the marriages with non-Catholic parties. You need to be prepared for dealing with the detailed catalogue of paperwork. Theoretically, the wedding ceremony takes place in the outer hall, but for Catholic weddings wedding ceremony takes place in a church. Including the pre-nuptial document, the marriage needs to be confirmed by the parish priest who is responsible for recording the marriage. The Catholic Church permits those who have divorced to receive church sacraments. However, he or she must come before a bishop for judgment.

The pre-nuptial document enables the local Church to review a couple’s previous marital records if there are any. The ceremony should be officiated by a minister.

Marriage with a foreigner

If you are a foreigner and intend to settle in the country, you need to pass through a series of legal requirements. In order to be an official resident of the country you will need a passport. A visa is mandatory. Be careful to get the most recent visa. Plan and apply for several months in advance for both. The requirements for entry are different for US and UK nationals.
